{"title_page": "Harriet Anena", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n|birth_name   = Harriet Anena\n| image       = Portrait of Harriet Anena.jpg\n|\n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place = [[Gulu District]], [[Uganda]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Poet, journalist\n| nationality = Ugandan\n| alma_mater    = [[Makerere University]]<br />{{small|(Bachelor of Arts in [[mass communication]])}}<br />{{small|([[Master of Arts]] in human rights)}}\n| genre       = Poetry, fiction\n| subject     =\n| notableworks = ''A Nation In Labour'' (2015)\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| awards      =2018 [[Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature in Africa]]\n| Twitter     =\n| website     = {{URL|https://anenah.wordpress.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Harriet Anena''' is a [[Uganda]]n writer whose works include poetry<ref name=\"jamesmurua.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jamesmurua.com/ugandan-poet-harriet-anena-showcases-in-kampala/|title=Ugandan poet Harriet Anena showcases in Kampala|author=James Murua|date=25 February 2015|publisher=jamesmurua.com|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>, nonfiction and fiction. She is the author of a collection of poems, ''A Nation In Labour'', published in 2015.<ref name=somanystories>{{cite web | url=http://somanystories.ug/reviews/2015/02/book-review-nation-labour-three-voices-one-book | title=Book Review: A Nation In Labour - Three voices, one book |authors=Richard Oduor; Grace Kenganzi; David Kangye| publisher= somanystories.ug |date=March 2015|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Anena worked with the ''[[Daily Monitor]]'' newspaper as a reporter, sub-editor, and deputy chief sub-editor from 2009 to September 2014. Her journalistic articles have been published in the ''Daily Monitor'',<ref name=mo-n-itor>{{cite web | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/OpEd/Commentary/If-Uganda--divorced--colonialism--why-are-we-on/-/689364/1629784/-/113668rz/-/index.html |author= Harriet Anena| title=If Uganda \u2018divorced\u2019 colonialism, why are we on our knees over aid cuts? |work=Daily Monitor |date=27 November 2012| accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=mo-n-i-tor>{{cite web |author= Harriet Anena| url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/OpEd/Commentary/-/689364/1314454/-/129lu16z/-/index.html | title=Govt must live up to its mandate and tackle the nodding disease |work=Daily Monitor |date=27 January 2012| accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> ''[[New Vision]]'', and ''[[The Observer (Uganda)|The Observer]]''. She has also taught specialised writing at the [[Islamic University in Uganda]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nAnena was born to [[Acholi people|Acholi]] parents and raised in the [[Gulu District]] of Uganda.<ref name=shortstorydayafrica.org>{{cite web | url=http://shortstorydayafrica.org/news/for-me-life-is-political | title='For Me, Life Is Political.' An Interview With Harriet Anena | publisher=Short Story Day Africa |date=30 September 2015| accessdate= 2 October 2015}}</ref> She attended Gulu Public Primary School, Sacred Heart Secondary School, and Gulu Central High School. She graduated with a Bachelor of Mass Communication degree from [[Makerere University]] in 2010 and completed a Master of Arts degree in human rights from the same institution in 2015.<ref name=\"monitor\">{{cite web |author= Joseph Ssemutooke|url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/artsculture/Reviews/making-budding-poet/-/691232/2615400/-/11yvvy0z/-/index.html | title= The making of a budding poet| work= Daily Monitor |date=7 February 2015| accessdate= 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nAnena wrote her first poem, \"The plight of the Acholi child\", in 2003. It won a writing competition organised by the Acholi Religious Leaders Peace Initiative and helped secure her a bursary for A-Level education.<ref name=\"monitor\"/> She attended the 2013 [[Caine Prize]] workshop held in Uganda,<ref name=caineprize>{{cite web | title=Creative minds assemble by Lake Victoria: reflections on the 2013 Caine Prize workshop|author= Lizzy Attree | url=http://caineprize.blogspot.com/2014/02/this-is-belated-post-on-uganda-workshop.html |date=11 February 2014| accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=moonchild09>{{cite web |author=[[Abubakar Adam Ibrahim]]|title=Ten Days at the Caine Prize Writing Workshop | url=https://moonchild09.wordpress.com/tag/lillian-aujo |publisher=Moonchild's Temple|date=12 May 2013| accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> and her story \"Watchdog Games\" was published in the anthology ''A Memory This Size and Other Stories: The Caine Prize for African Writing 2013''.<ref name=m-o-nit-or>{{cite web | title=Caine prize anthology launched|date=27 April 2013|work=Daily Monitor|author= Dennis D. Muhumuza|url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/artsculture/Reviews/Caine-prize-anthology-launched/-/691232/1759300/-/oh9h7l/-/index.html | accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> In 2013, she was shortlisted for the \"Ghana Poetry prize\" for her poem \"We arise\".<ref name=poetryfoundationghana>{{cite web | url=http://www.poetryfoundationghana.org/index.php/en/featured/poetry-news/item/800-shortlist-for-ghana-poetry-prize-2013-released | title=Shortlist for Ghana Poetry Prize 2013 Released | publisher=poetryfoundationghana.org | accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n''A Nation In Labour'', published in 2015, is her debut book,<ref name=magunga>{{cite web | url=http://www.magunga.com/a-nation-in-labour | title=A Nation In Labour| author=Oduor Jagero|work=The Magunga |date=15 March 2015| accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> a \"socially conscious\" collection of poems, about which she has said: \"I explore my experiences as a child who lived through the [[LRA]] insurgency in northern Uganda and the post-war period. Today, I still keenly watch how people are piecing back the torn pieces of their lives; but also the post-war challenge.\"<ref>Bridget Boakye (27 February 2018), [https://face2faceafrica.com/article/poetic-attack-a-nation-in-labour-ugandan-poet-harriet-anena \"Poetic Attack: \u2018A Nation In Labour\u2019 by Ugandan poet Harriet Anena\"], ''Face2face Africa''.</ref> The reviewer for ''New Vision'' wrote: \"Anena and her buffet of poetry will keep you hooked.\"<ref>Caroline Ariba (27 June 2016), [https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1427988/book-review-nation-labour \"Book review: A nation is in labour\"], ''New Vision''.</ref> As described by Tomiwa Ilori, \"''A Nation in Labour'' is a four-part treatise that uses elevated language to tell of horror. Anena\u2019s collection of poetry warns society about its warped value system through a disciplined use of satiric responses that resonate. Each part of the treatise soaks our dessicated humanity in fluid cadences.\"<ref>Tomiwa Ilori, [http://wawabookreview.com/2015/10/27/rhetoric-of-pain-and-other-resources/ \"Rhetoric of Pain and Other Resources\"], ''Wawa Book Review'', 27 October 2015.</ref> The Ugandan ''[[The Observer (Uganda)|Observer]]'''s review said: \"Anena craftily uses simple language, but with diction that leaves the reader challenged to take action to better the situation.\"<ref>Angella Tusiime, [https://www.observer.ug/education/37034-book-review-anena-pens-out-a-nation-in-labour \"Book review: Anena pens out a nation in labour\"], ''The Observer'' (Uganda), 29 March 2015.</ref> In November 2018, ''A Nation In Labour'' was shortlisted for the biennial [[Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature in Africa]], alongside collections by [[Tanure Ojaide]] and Servio Gbadamosi.<ref>[https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2018/11/03/nine-african-poets-shortlisted-for-2018-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature/ \"Nine African poets shortlisted for 2018 Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature\"], ''P.M. News'', 3 November 2018.</ref><ref>''Daily Graphic'' (19 November 2018), [https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/9-african-poets-on-2018-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-list.html \"9 African poets on 2018 Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature list\"], ''Graphic Online''.</ref><ref>[https://www.thecable.ng/arena-ojaide-gbadamosi-shortlisted-for-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature \"Arena, Ojaide, Gbadamosi shortlisted for Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature\"], ''The Cable'', 28 November 2018,</ref><ref>[http://www.jamesmurua.com/wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-2018-shortlist-announced/ \"Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature 2018 shortlist announced\"], James Murua's Literature Blog, 29 November 2018.</ref> On 9 December 2018, at an award ceremony held in [[Lagos]], Anena and Ojaide were announced as joint winners, chosen by judges [[Toyin Falola]], Olu Obafemi and [[Margaret Busby]], the presentation being made by Professor [[Wole Soyinka]].<ref>[http://www.jamesmurua.com/prof-tanure-ojaide-harriet-anena-are-joint-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-2018-winners/ \"Prof Tanure Ojaide, Harriet Anena are joint Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature 2018 winners\"], James Murua's Literature Blog, 10 December 2018.</ref><ref>Joseph Kizza, [https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1491013/ugandan-wins-2018-wole-soyinka-prize-literature \"Ugandan wins 2018 Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature\"], ''New Vision'', 10 December 2018.</ref><ref>Kungu Al-Mahadi Adam, [https://www.softpower.ug/ugandan-author-harriet-anena-wins-2018-wole-soyinka-prize/ \"Ugandan Author, Harriet Anena Wins 2018 Wole Soyinka Prize\"], SoftPower News'', 10 December 2018.</ref>\n\nAnena's short story \"Dancing with Ma\" was longlisted for the 2018 [[Commonwealth Short Story Prize]].<ref>[http://www.commonwealthwriters.org/2018-cssp-shortlist/ \"2018 Commonwealth Short Story Prize Shortlist\"], Commonwealth Writers, 23 May 2018.</ref><ref>Bamuturaki Musinguzi (10 November 2018), [https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/magazine/Ugandan-poet-longlisted-for-Wole-Soyinka-prize/434746-4844816-8y5g2nz/index.html \"Ugandan poet longlisted for Wole Soyinka prize\"], ''The East African''.</ref> She is a contributor to the 2019 anthology ''[[New Daughters of Africa]]''.<ref>Jamal Tuschick, [https://www.textland-online.de/index.php?article_id=896 \"African Book Festival 2019 | Your next good read\"], ''Textland'', 4 April 2019.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn December 2018, Harriet Anena was named as joint winner of the 2018 [[Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature in Africa]] for her book ''A Nation in Labour'', published in 2015.<ref>Ninsiima Julian, [http://www.pmldaily.com/news/2018/12/ugandas-harriet-anena-of-acugandas-harriet-anena-wins-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-in-africa-2018me-wins-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-in-africa.html \"Uganda\u2019s Harriet Anena wins Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature in Africa 2018\"], ''PML Daily'', 10 December 2018.</ref><ref>[https://edge.ug/2018/12/10/ugandan-writer-harriet-anena-wins-wole-soyinka-literature-prize/ \"Ugandan writer Harriet Anena wins Wole Soyinka Literature Prize\"], ''Edge'', 10 December 2018.</ref> She jointly won the prize with Professor [[Tanure Ojaide]]. Anena received her award at a ceremony in Lagos, Nigeria, attended by [[Wole Soyinka]], Africa\u2019s first Nobel Laureate in literature, after whom the prize is named. The Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature is a \"pan-African writing prize awarded biennially to the best literary work produced by an African\".<ref>{{cite web|date=10 December 2018 | url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Ugandan-author-Anena-Soyinka-Literature-Ojaide-prize/688334-4888872-o5j6ad/index.html |title=Ugandan author is joint winner of Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |access-date=10 December 2018 |author=Monitor Reporter |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n\n===Poetry collections===\n* {{cite book|title=A Nation In Labour|publisher= Millennium Press Limited|location=Kampala, Uganda| year= 2015| isbn= }}\n* ''Set Me On Fire''<ref>Harriet Anena, [https://africanwriterstrust.org/the-awt-conference-set-me-on-fire-by-harriet-anena/ \"The AWT Conference Set Me On Fire\"], [[African Writers Trust]], 24 March 2017.</ref>\n\n===Selected poems===\n* \"Forgiveness\" and \"We Arise\", in {{cite book|title=A Thousand Voices Rising: An anthology of contemporary African poetry|editor=Beverley Nambozo Nsengiyunva|publisher= BN Poetry Foundation|year= 2014|ISBN= 978-9970-9234-0-3}}\n* [http://enkare.org/sharing-man-country-harriet-anena/ \"Sharing My Man With A Country\"] in ''[[Enkare Review]]'', 15 September 2016\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160822024458/http://www.lawino-magazine.com/2014/08/poetry-violent-love-harriet-anena.html \"Violent Love\"] in ''Lawino'', 2014\n* [http://www.africanwriterstrust.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/suubi.pdf \"I Died Alive\"] in The Suubi Collection (2013)\n\n===Selected short stories===\n* \"Watchdog Games\" in {{cite book|title=A Memory This Size and Other Stories: The Caine Prize for African Writing 2013| publisher= Jacana media| year= 2013| isbn=9781431408382}}\n* [http://somanystories.ug/features/short-stories/2014/07/dogs-hungry-harriet-anena \"The Dogs Are Hungry \"] in \"Sooo Many Stories\", 2014 \n* [http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2014/05/02/writivism-flash-fiction-friday-early-for-nwacheta-games-of-guilt-a-question-of-underwear-and-the-axe/ \"The Axe\"] in ''Bookslive'', 2 May 2014.\n\n===Selected articles===\n* [http://www.monitor.co.ug/OpEd/Commentary/Let-the-north-hold-the-hoe-to-break-the-soil-and-not-from-Uganda/-/689364/1705324/-/xgep2fz/-/index.html \"Let the north hold the hoe to break the soil and not break away from Uganda\"], ''Daily Monitor'', 27 February 2013.\n* [http://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/PeoplePower/Child-labour-should-be-a-concern-for-all/-/689844/1734666/-/r4rjen/-/index.html \"Child labour should be a concern for all\"], ''Daily Monitor'', 31 March 2013.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://anenah.wordpress.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anena, Harriet}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women short story writers]]\n[[Category:Ugandan short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ugandan women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Gulu District]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ugandan poets]]\n[[Category:Kumusha]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women journalists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n|birth_name   = Harriet Anena\n| image       = Portrait of Harriet Anena.jpg\n|\n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place = [[Gulu District]], [[Uganda]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Poet, journalist\n| nationality = Ugandan\n| alma_mater    = [[Makerere University]]<br />{{small|(Bachelor of Arts in [[mass communication]])}}<br />{{small|([[Master of Arts]] in human rights)}}\n| genre       = Poetry, fiction\n| subject     =\n| notableworks = ''A Nation In Labour'' (2015)\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| awards      =2018 [[Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature in Africa]]\n| Twitter     =\n| website     = {{URL|https://anenah.wordpress.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Harriet Anena''' is a [[Uganda]]n author,<ref name=acholitimes>{{cite web | url=http://www.acholitimes.com/index.php/perspectives/interview/3011-harriet-anena | title=Harriet Anena | publisher=acholitimes.com | accessdate=17 March 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402141246/http://www.acholitimes.com/index.php/perspectives/interview/3011-harriet-anena | archivedate=2 April 2015 }}</ref> poet,<ref name=jamesmurua.com>{{cite web | url=http://www.jamesmurua.com/ugandan-poet-harriet-anena-showcases-in-kampala/ | title=Ugandan poet Harriet Anena showcases in Kampala |author=James Murua| publisher=jamesmurua.com |date=25 February 2015| accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> and journalist.<ref name=moni-tor>{{cite web | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/PeoplePower/Mr-President--how-much-do-you-know-about--conflict-resolution-/-/689844/2029612/-/fp37xl/-/index.html |author=Harriet Anena| title=Mr President, how much do you know about conflict resolution?| work= Daily Monitor |date=13 October 2013| accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> She is the author of a collection of poems, ''A Nation In Labour'', published in 2015.<ref name=somanystories>{{cite web | url=http://somanystories.ug/reviews/2015/02/book-review-nation-labour-three-voices-one-book | title=Book Review: A Nation In Labour - Three voices, one book |authors=Richard Oduor; Grace Kenganzi; David Kangye| publisher= somanystories.ug |date=March 2015|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Anena worked with the ''[[Daily Monitor]]'' newspaper as a reporter, sub-editor, and deputy chief sub-editor from 2009 to September 2014. Her journalistic articles have been published in the ''Daily Monitor'',<ref name=mo-n-itor>{{cite web | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/OpEd/Commentary/If-Uganda--divorced--colonialism--why-are-we-on/-/689364/1629784/-/113668rz/-/index.html |author= Harriet Anena| title=If Uganda \u2018divorced\u2019 colonialism, why are we on our knees over aid cuts? |work=Daily Monitor |date=27 November 2012| accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=mo-n-i-tor>{{cite web |author= Harriet Anena| url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/OpEd/Commentary/-/689364/1314454/-/129lu16z/-/index.html | title=Govt must live up to its mandate and tackle the nodding disease |work=Daily Monitor |date=27 January 2012| accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> ''[[New Vision]]'', and ''[[The Observer (Uganda)|The Observer]]''. She has also taught specialised writing at the [[Islamic University in Uganda]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nAnena was born to [[Acholi people|Acholi]] parents and raised in the [[Gulu District]] of Uganda.<ref name=shortstorydayafrica.org>{{cite web | url=http://shortstorydayafrica.org/news/for-me-life-is-political | title='For Me, Life Is Political.' An Interview With Harriet Anena | publisher=Short Story Day Africa |date=30 September 2015| accessdate= 2 October 2015}}</ref> She attended Gulu Public Primary School, Sacred Heart Secondary School, and Gulu Central High School. She graduated with a Bachelor of Mass Communication degree from [[Makerere University]] in 2010 and completed a Master of Arts degree in human rights from the same institution in 2015.<ref name=\"monitor\">{{cite web |author= Joseph Ssemutooke|url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/artsculture/Reviews/making-budding-poet/-/691232/2615400/-/11yvvy0z/-/index.html | title= The making of a budding poet| work= Daily Monitor |date=7 February 2015| accessdate= 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nAnena wrote her first poem, \"The plight of the Acholi child\", in 2003. It won a writing competition organised by the Acholi Religious Leaders Peace Initiative and helped secure her a bursary for A-Level education.<ref name=\"monitor\"/> She attended the 2013 [[Caine Prize]] workshop held in Uganda,<ref name=caineprize>{{cite web | title=Creative minds assemble by Lake Victoria: reflections on the 2013 Caine Prize workshop|author= Lizzy Attree | url=http://caineprize.blogspot.com/2014/02/this-is-belated-post-on-uganda-workshop.html |date=11 February 2014| accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=moonchild09>{{cite web |author=[[Abubakar Adam Ibrahim]]|title=Ten Days at the Caine Prize Writing Workshop | url=https://moonchild09.wordpress.com/tag/lillian-aujo |publisher=Moonchild's Temple|date=12 May 2013| accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> and her story \"Watchdog Games\" was published in the anthology ''A Memory This Size and Other Stories: The Caine Prize for African Writing 2013''.<ref name=m-o-nit-or>{{cite web | title=Caine prize anthology launched|date=27 April 2013|work=Daily Monitor|author= Dennis D. Muhumuza|url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/artsculture/Reviews/Caine-prize-anthology-launched/-/691232/1759300/-/oh9h7l/-/index.html | accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> In 2013, she was shortlisted for the \"Ghana Poetry prize\" for her poem \"We arise\".<ref name=poetryfoundationghana>{{cite web | url=http://www.poetryfoundationghana.org/index.php/en/featured/poetry-news/item/800-shortlist-for-ghana-poetry-prize-2013-released | title=Shortlist for Ghana Poetry Prize 2013 Released | publisher=poetryfoundationghana.org | accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n''A Nation In Labour'', published in 2015, is her debut book,<ref name=magunga>{{cite web | url=http://www.magunga.com/a-nation-in-labour | title=A Nation In Labour| author=Oduor Jagero|work=The Magunga |date=15 March 2015| accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> a \"socially conscious\" collection of poems, about which she has said: \"I explore my experiences as a child who lived through the [[LRA]] insurgency in northern Uganda and the post-war period. Today, I still keenly watch how people are piecing back the torn pieces of their lives; but also the post-war challenge.\"<ref>Bridget Boakye (27 February 2018), [https://face2faceafrica.com/article/poetic-attack-a-nation-in-labour-ugandan-poet-harriet-anena \"Poetic Attack: \u2018A Nation In Labour\u2019 by Ugandan poet Harriet Anena\"], ''Face2face Africa''.</ref> The reviewer for ''New Vision'' wrote: \"Anena and her buffet of poetry will keep you hooked.\"<ref>Caroline Ariba (27 June 2016), [https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1427988/book-review-nation-labour \"Book review: A nation is in labour\"], ''New Vision''.</ref> As described by Tomiwa Ilori, \"''A Nation in Labour'' is a four-part treatise that uses elevated language to tell of horror. Anena\u2019s collection of poetry warns society about its warped value system through a disciplined use of satiric responses that resonate. Each part of the treatise soaks our dessicated humanity in fluid cadences.\"<ref>Tomiwa Ilori, [http://wawabookreview.com/2015/10/27/rhetoric-of-pain-and-other-resources/ \"Rhetoric of Pain and Other Resources\"], ''Wawa Book Review'', 27 October 2015.</ref> The Ugandan ''[[The Observer (Uganda)|Observer]]'''s review said: \"Anena craftily uses simple language, but with diction that leaves the reader challenged to take action to better the situation.\"<ref>Angella Tusiime, [https://www.observer.ug/education/37034-book-review-anena-pens-out-a-nation-in-labour \"Book review: Anena pens out a nation in labour\"], ''The Observer'' (Uganda), 29 March 2015.</ref> In November 2018, ''A Nation In Labour'' was shortlisted for the biennial [[Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature in Africa]], alongside collections by [[Tanure Ojaide]] and Servio Gbadamosi.<ref>[https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2018/11/03/nine-african-poets-shortlisted-for-2018-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature/ \"Nine African poets shortlisted for 2018 Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature\"], ''P.M. News'', 3 November 2018.</ref><ref>''Daily Graphic'' (19 November 2018), [https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/9-african-poets-on-2018-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-list.html \"9 African poets on 2018 Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature list\"], ''Graphic Online''.</ref><ref>[https://www.thecable.ng/arena-ojaide-gbadamosi-shortlisted-for-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature \"Arena, Ojaide, Gbadamosi shortlisted for Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature\"], ''The Cable'', 28 November 2018,</ref><ref>[http://www.jamesmurua.com/wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-2018-shortlist-announced/ \"Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature 2018 shortlist announced\"], James Murua's Literature Blog, 29 November 2018.</ref> On 9 December 2018, at an award ceremony held in [[Lagos]], Anena and Ojaide were announced as joint winners, chosen by judges [[Toyin Falola]], Olu Obafemi and [[Margaret Busby]], the presentation being made by Professor [[Wole Soyinka]].<ref>[http://www.jamesmurua.com/prof-tanure-ojaide-harriet-anena-are-joint-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-2018-winners/ \"Prof Tanure Ojaide, Harriet Anena are joint Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature 2018 winners\"], James Murua's Literature Blog, 10 December 2018.</ref><ref>Joseph Kizza, [https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1491013/ugandan-wins-2018-wole-soyinka-prize-literature \"Ugandan wins 2018 Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature\"], ''New Vision'', 10 December 2018.</ref><ref>Kungu Al-Mahadi Adam, [https://www.softpower.ug/ugandan-author-harriet-anena-wins-2018-wole-soyinka-prize/ \"Ugandan Author, Harriet Anena Wins 2018 Wole Soyinka Prize\"], SoftPower News'', 10 December 2018.</ref>\n\nAnena's short story \"Dancing with Ma\" was longlisted for the 2018 [[Commonwealth Short Story Prize]].<ref>[http://www.commonwealthwriters.org/2018-cssp-shortlist/ \"2018 Commonwealth Short Story Prize Shortlist\"], Commonwealth Writers, 23 May 2018.</ref><ref>Bamuturaki Musinguzi (10 November 2018), [https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/magazine/Ugandan-poet-longlisted-for-Wole-Soyinka-prize/434746-4844816-8y5g2nz/index.html \"Ugandan poet longlisted for Wole Soyinka prize\"], ''The East African''.</ref> She is a contributor to the 2019 anthology ''[[New Daughters of Africa]]''.<ref>Jamal Tuschick, [https://www.textland-online.de/index.php?article_id=896 \"African Book Festival 2019 | Your next good read\"], ''Textland'', 4 April 2019.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn December 2018, Harriet Anena was named as joint winner of the 2018 [[Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature in Africa]] for her book ''A Nation in Labour'', published in 2015.<ref>Ninsiima Julian, [http://www.pmldaily.com/news/2018/12/ugandas-harriet-anena-of-acugandas-harriet-anena-wins-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-in-africa-2018me-wins-wole-soyinka-prize-for-literature-in-africa.html \"Uganda\u2019s Harriet Anena wins Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature in Africa 2018\"], ''PML Daily'', 10 December 2018.</ref><ref>[https://edge.ug/2018/12/10/ugandan-writer-harriet-anena-wins-wole-soyinka-literature-prize/ \"Ugandan writer Harriet Anena wins Wole Soyinka Literature Prize\"], ''Edge'', 10 December 2018.</ref> She jointly won the prize with Professor [[Tanure Ojaide]]. Anena received her award at a ceremony in Lagos, Nigeria, attended by [[Wole Soyinka]], Africa\u2019s first Nobel Laureate in literature, after whom the prize is named. The Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature is a \"pan-African writing prize awarded biennially to the best literary work produced by an African\".<ref>{{cite web|date=10 December 2018 | url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Ugandan-author-Anena-Soyinka-Literature-Ojaide-prize/688334-4888872-o5j6ad/index.html |title=Ugandan author is joint winner of Wole Soyinka Prize for Literature |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |access-date=10 December 2018 |author=Monitor Reporter |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n\n===Poetry collections===\n* {{cite book|title=A Nation In Labour|publisher= Millennium Press Limited|location=Kampala, Uganda| year= 2015| isbn= }}\n* ''Set Me On Fire''<ref>Harriet Anena, [https://africanwriterstrust.org/the-awt-conference-set-me-on-fire-by-harriet-anena/ \"The AWT Conference Set Me On Fire\"], [[African Writers Trust]], 24 March 2017.</ref>\n\n===Selected poems===\n* \"Forgiveness\" and \"We Arise\", in {{cite book|title=A Thousand Voices Rising: An anthology of contemporary African poetry|editor=Beverley Nambozo Nsengiyunva|publisher= BN Poetry Foundation|year= 2014|ISBN= 978-9970-9234-0-3}}\n* [http://enkare.org/sharing-man-country-harriet-anena/ \"Sharing My Man With A Country\"] in ''[[Enkare Review]]'', 15 September 2016\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160822024458/http://www.lawino-magazine.com/2014/08/poetry-violent-love-harriet-anena.html \"Violent Love\"] in ''Lawino'', 2014\n* [http://www.africanwriterstrust.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/suubi.pdf \"I Died Alive\"] in The Suubi Collection (2013)\n\n===Selected short stories===\n* \"Watchdog Games\" in {{cite book|title=A Memory This Size and Other Stories: The Caine Prize for African Writing 2013| publisher= Jacana media| year= 2013| isbn=9781431408382}}\n* [http://somanystories.ug/features/short-stories/2014/07/dogs-hungry-harriet-anena \"The Dogs Are Hungry \"] in \"Sooo Many Stories\", 2014 \n* [http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2014/05/02/writivism-flash-fiction-friday-early-for-nwacheta-games-of-guilt-a-question-of-underwear-and-the-axe/ \"The Axe\"] in ''Bookslive'', 2 May 2014.\n\n===Selected articles===\n* [http://www.monitor.co.ug/OpEd/Commentary/Let-the-north-hold-the-hoe-to-break-the-soil-and-not-from-Uganda/-/689364/1705324/-/xgep2fz/-/index.html \"Let the north hold the hoe to break the soil and not break away from Uganda\"], ''Daily Monitor'', 27 February 2013.\n* [http://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/PeoplePower/Child-labour-should-be-a-concern-for-all/-/689844/1734666/-/r4rjen/-/index.html \"Child labour should be a concern for all\"], ''Daily Monitor'', 31 March 2013.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://anenah.wordpress.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anena, Harriet}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women short story writers]]\n[[Category:Ugandan short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ugandan women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Gulu District]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ugandan poets]]\n[[Category:Kumusha]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women journalists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Hanena26", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harriet_Anena"}
{"title_page": "Government in exile of the Commonwealth of the Philippines", "text_new": "{{Infobox geopolitical organization\n|name =              Commonwealth of the Philippines<br />\n(government in exile)\n|native_name =       <!-- Long-form name in native or any/all non-English languages -->\n|linking_name =      <!-- For wikilinks, if diff from name -->\n|image_flag =        Flag of the Philippines (1946\u20131985, 1986\u20131998).svg<!-- taken from the [[Flag of the Philippines]] article. Should probably be shown inverted as the war flag. -->\n|alt_flag =          <!-- alt text for flag-->\n|flag_border =       <!--set to no to disable border around the flag-->\n|symbol_type =       <!-- Symbol, Emblem, Logo, etc. -->\n|image_symbol =      <!-- Symbol image's filename -->\n|alt_symbol =        <!-- alt text for symbol -->\n|symbol_width =      <!-- Symbol image's width (default 85px) -->\n|motto =             <!-- \"[motto]\" -->\n|englishmotto =      <!--English language version of motto-->\n|anthem =            <!-- ''[anthem name]'' -->\n|text_symbol_type =  <!-- for other types of text symbol -->\n|text_symbol =       <!-- e.g. ''[hymn name]'' -->\n|image_map =         <!-- Map image's filename -->\n|loctext =           <!--text description of location of organization-->\n|alt_map =           <!-- alt text for map image -->\n|map_width =         <!-- Map image's width (default 250px) -->\n|map_caption = \n|org_type =          <!-- e.g. Trade bloc -->\n|membership_type =   <!-- (default \"Membership\") -->\n|membership =        <!-- Type/s and/or number/s of members -->\n|admin_center_type = <!-- e.g. \"Administrative center\" (default) -->\n|admin_center =      <!-- Location/s of administrative center/s -->\n|languages_type =    <!-- e.g. \"[[Official language]]s\" (default) -->\n|languages = \n|leader_title1 =     President\n|leader_name1 = \nManuel L. Quezon (1942&mdash;1944)<br />\nSergio Osme\u00f1a (1944&mdash;1945)\n|leader_title2 =     Vice President<br />\n|leader_name2 = Sergio Osme\u00f1a (1942&mdash;1944)<br />\nVacant (1944&mdash;1945)\n|leader_title14 = \n|leader_name14 =\n|established =      May 13, 1942<ref name=\"Talmon1998p295\">{{cite book|last=Talmon|first=Stefan|title=Recognition of Governments in International Law: With Particular Reference to Governments in Exile|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=scc8EboiJX8C|year=1998|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=978-0-19-826573-3|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=scc8EboiJX8C&pg=PA295 295]}}</ref>\n|established_event1 = \n|established_date1 = \n|established_event2 = \n|established_date2 = \n<!--......-->\n|established_event9 = \n|established_date9 = \n|official_website = \n|area_km2 =          <!-- major area size (in sq_km) -->\n|area_sq_mi =        <!-- area in square mi (requires area_km2) -->\n|area_footnote =     <!-- optional footnote for area -->\n|percent_water = \n|area_label =        <!-- label under \"Area\" (default is \"Total\") -->\n|area_label2 =       <!-- label below area_label (optional) -->\n|area_dabodyalign =  <!-- text after area_label2 (optional) -->\n|population_estimate = \n|population_estimate_year = \n|population_density_km2 = \n|population_density_sq_mi = \n|GDP_PPP = \n|GDP_PPP_rank = \n|GDP_PPP_year = \n|GDP_PPP_per_capita = \n|GDP_nominal = \n|GDP_nominal_year = \n|GDP_nominal_per_capita = \n|Gini =              <!-- number only, 0-100 -->\n|Gini_ref =          <!-- for any ref/s to associate with Gini number -->\n|Gini_year = \n|HDI =               <!-- number only, 0-1 -->\n|HDI_ref =           <!-- for any ref/s to associate with HDI number -->\n|HDI_year = \n|currency = \n|currency_code = \n|time_zone = \n|utc_offset =        <!-- +N, where N is number of hours -->\n|footnote1 = \n|footnote2 = \n<!--......-->\n|footnote7 = \n|footnotes =         <!-- For generic non-numbered footnotes -->\n}}\n\n==Background==\nOn the morning of 8 December, 1941, the Japanese [[Philippines campaign (1941\u20131942)#Invasion|invaded the Philippines]]. The invasion began with [[Japanese invasion of Batan Island|landings at Bataan Island]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Morton|first=Louis|title=The Fall of the Philippines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xS5BvQEACAAJ|year=1978|publisher=Department of the Army|isbn=978-0-7581-7385-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Morton|first=Louis|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USA/USA-P-PI/USA-P-PI-6.html|title=Chapter VI: The First Landings|series=[http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USA/USA-P-PI/The Fall of the Philippines]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> and followed the [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|bombing]] of the U.S. base at Pearl Harbor a few hours earlier. President [[Manuel L. Quezon]] was in [[Baguio]] recuperating from a recurrence of an old illness, and immediately traveled by road the 160 miles to Manila to take charge of the Filipino resistance. In meetings following his arrival, U.S. [[Douglas MacArthur|General MacArthur]] informed him that MacArthur would be transferring his headquarters to [[Corregidor|Corregidor island]], and requested the President to join him. President Quezon initially objected, but agreed when his [[Cabinet of the Philippines|Cabinet]] endorsed MacArthur's suggestion by unanimous decision. On December 24, the President relocated there, accompanied by his family, Vice President [[Sergio Osme\u00f1a|Vice President Osme\u00f1a]], Chief Justice Santos, Major. General Valdes, who had been designated Secretary of National Defense, and some members of the Executive Staff. President Quezon and Vice President Osmeiia began their second term on Corregidor on [[Rizal Day]], December 30, 1941.{{sfn|Pabico|2006|p=54}}<ref name=Philippines1943> {{cite journal|title=The Philippine Government : from Manila to Washington|journal=Philippines|publisher=The Commonwealth of the Philippines|volume=III|issue=1|date=March 15, 1943}} (see also {{cite web|url=https://repository.mainlib.upd.edu.ph/s/rare-periodicals/media/4311|title=The Philippine Government from Manila to Washington|publisher=University of the Philippines Diliman|accessdate=March 13, 2020}})</ref>\n\nAs invading Japanese forces advanced, all [[United States Army Forces in the Far East]] (USAFFE) military personnel were removed from the major urban areas. Manila was officially declared an [[open city]] on 26 December. By then, USAFFE forces had withdrawn to the Bataan peninsula and were under siege there. By the middle of February the lack of food on Corregidor had become acute, and it was decided chat the President could be of more help by going to the unoccupied provinces to organize some plan of bringing in food for the soldiers at Bataan and Corregidor and to keep up the morale of the civilian population. At dusk on February 20, the American submarine [[USS Swordfish (SS-193)]] slipped through mine fields, was boarded by President Quezon and his party<!-- composed of? supporting cite for composition? -->, and transported them to [[Iloilo]], which had not yet been occupied by Japanese forces.<ref name=Philippines1943 /> The following night, they boarded the ship ''Princess of Negros'', which transported them to [[Dumaguete]].<ref name=quezon2001>{{cite web|url=https://philippinesfreepress.wordpress.com/2001/12/08/escape-from-corregidor-december-8-2001/|title=Escape from Corregidor, December 8, 2001|last=Quezon|first=Manuel III|year=2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.history.navy.mil/research/library/online-reading-room/title-list-alphabetically/u/united-states-submarine-losses/swordfish-ss-193.html|title=Swordfish (SS 193)|publisher=Naval History and Heritage Command|accessdate=March 11, 2020<!-- NOTE: contains some info re the makeyp of Quezon's party-->}}</ref> General MacArthur and his party, meanwhile, had been evacuated from Corregidor by [[PT boat]] to [[Cagayan de Oro]] on [[Mindanao]] (see [[Douglas MacArthur's escape from the Philippines]]).\n\n==The Emergency Powers Act==\nOn December 16, 1941, President Quezon approved Commonwealth Act No. 671, which had been passed by the Philippine Legislature. This act declared a state of total emergency and invested the President with extraordinary powers in order to meet the emergency. Generally, the act authorized the President, during the existence of the emergency, to promulgate such rules and regulations as he may deem necessary to carry out the national policy. These powers included authority to transfer the seat of the Government or component parts of the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1941/12/16/commonwealth-act-no-671/|title=Commonwealth Act No. 671 : AN ACT DECLARING A STATE OF TOTAL EMERGENCY AS A RESULT OF WAR INVOLVING THE PHILIPPINES AND AUTHORIZING THE PRESIDENT TO PROMULGATE RULES AND REGULATIONS TO MEET SUCH EMERGENCY|website=officialgazette.gov.ph|date=December 16, 1941}}</ref>\n\n==Evacuation from the Philippines==\nMacArthur had sent some of the boats which had evacuated his party back to the southern tip of [[Negros Island]] to pick up President Quezon's party.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sandler|first=Stanley|title=World War II in the Pacific: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5iT6orBAT0gC|year=2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-58199-2|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=5iT6orBAT0gC&pg=PA198&dq=quezon 198]}}</ref> Major Soriano, President Quezon's aide, met boat [[PT-41]] and redirected it to [[Dumaguete]], where it embarked President Quezon's party and transported them to [[Oroquieta]] in what was then the province of [[Misamis (province)|Misamis]].<ref name=quezon2001 /> From there, they traveled<!-- how?--> to the Del Monte plantation on [[Mindanao]], where they remained overnight and were picked up the following day at [[Del Monte Airfield]] by two [[B-17]] aircraft that transported them to [[Batchelor Airfiel]]d in Northern Australia, where they transferred to [[Douglas DC-5]] aircraft for transport to [[Alice Springs]]. There, they were reunited with the party of Vice President Osme\u00f1a that had been transported in a separate aircraft.<ref name=quezon2001 /> The parties flew together to [[Adelaide]], spent the night there, and took an overnight train to [[Melbourne]].<ref name=quezon2001 />\n\n[[File:Quezon Roosevelt.jpg|thumb|right|[[Manuel L. Quezon]] visiting [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] in Washington, D.C. while in exile]]\nPresident Quezon felt that he should be in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]. The U.S. government agreed and, in the Spring of 1942, the ''[[SS President Coolidge]]'', which had been pressed into service to evacuate U.S. citizens from parts of asia after the Japanese attacks and converted into a troopship, transported Quezon and his party to the U.S. escorted by the [[cruiser]] ''[[USS St. Louis]]'',<!-- blacklisted selfpub source <ref>{{cite book|last=Burdeos|first=Ray L.|title=Assemble in Agusan Valley: World War-Ii in Mindanao|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nFSfCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-5049-7840-8|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=nFSfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT73&dq=%22president+coolidge%22+quezon 73]}}</ref> --> departing Melbourne on April 20 and arriving in San Francisco on May 8.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Garcia|editor1-first=Mauro|editor2-last=Rivera|editor2-first=Juan F.|year=1978|url=https://archive.org/details/quezon-in-retrospect-philippine-historical-association-historical-bulletin-volume-xxii/page/n3/mode/2up|title=Quezon in Retrospect|chapter=Red Letter Days in President Manuel Luis Quezon's Life|chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/quezon-in-retrospect-philippine-historical-association-historical-bulletin-volume-xxii/page/n383/mode/2up|page=[https://archive.org/details/quezon-in-retrospect-philippine-historical-association-historical-bulletin-volume-xxii/page/n385/mode/2up 373]|publisher=The Philippine Historical Association}}</ref>\n\nQuezon and party were met in San Francisco, and military aides were assigned to escort the party on a special train which had been assigned to transport them to Washington D.C.<!-- the party was met by Assistant Secretary of the Interior [[Oscar L. Chapman]]. The cited source gives his name incorrectly as \"W.Chapman\".--> The train arrived in Washington on May 13, and was met by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] along with his wife, [[Eleanor Roosevelt|Eleanor]] and members of his [[Cabinet of the United States|Cabinet]]. Quezon and his family were transported by motorcade to the [[White House]]. They spent the night at the White House and were guests of honor the following day at a luncheon hosted by the Roosevelts to formally welcome the exiled Philippine Government to the Unites States, underscoring its legitimacy.{{sfn|Pabico|2006|p=74}}<!--\n\nNOTE TO EDITORS: There is a somewhat differing account in {{cite journal|title=The Philippine Government : from Manila to Washington|journal=Philippines|publisher=The Commonwealth of the Philippines|volume=III|issue=1|date=March 15, 1943}} (see also {{cite web|url=https://repository.mainlib.upd.edu.ph/s/rare-periodicals/media/4311|title=The Philippine Government from Manila to Washington|publisher=University of the Philippines Diliman|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}) If in Manila, this item may be available for viewing and, perhaps, for photocopying at UPD. (this item is mentioned in the References section). This article section probably needs a review to consider how differing accounts available in various sources should be handled here.\n\n-->\n\n==The government in exile==\n{{Quezon cabinet-in-exile|state=expanded}}\nMembers of the war cabinet were heavily involved in civic and social activities such as endorsing the sale of [[war bond]]s, participating in parades with heroic themes, involvement with commemoration and celebration of Philippine historic events such as [[Rizal Day]]. These activities were very successful in sustaining American interest in the Philippine Commonwealth, and had immense impact on the Japanese-occupied Philippines through shortwave news broadcasts which the Japanese were unable to stop. The government in exile also published a news magazine in the United States called ''Philippines''. President Quezon was invited by President Roosevelt to join the [[Pacific War Council]], and was asked to sign the United Nations Pact for the Philippines; in doing so, Quezon became a signatory of the [[Atlantic Charter]].{{sfn|Pabico|2006|p=77}} Representing the Philippine Government, on June 14, 1942, President Quezon signed the United Nations Pact of January 1, 1942, joining with the group of nations pledged as being \"engaged in a common struggle against save and brutal forces seeking to subjugate the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/Dip/UNPact.html|title=The United Nations Pact|website=ibiblio.org|date=January 1, 1942}}</ref>\n\nPresident Quezon had been elected to a six-year term as the second President of the Philippines and the first President of the Philippine Commonwealth, taking office on November 15, 1935.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/about/gov/exec/|title=The Executive Branch|website=officialgazette.gov.ph/|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> In 1940, The 1935 Constitution was amended by the [[National Assembly of the Philippines|National Assembly]] to change the legislature from a unicameral assembly to a bicameral congress and to change the term of office of the President from six years with no reelection to four years with a possibility of being reelected for a second term.<ref name=\"constitution day\">{{cite web|url=https://officialgazette.gov.ph/constitutions/constitution-day/|title=Constitution Day|website=officialgazette.gov.ph|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The amended constitution contained a provision saying, \"No person shall serve as President for more than eight consecutive years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/constitutions/1935-constitution-ammended/|title=1935 Constitution amended|website=officialgazette.gov.ph/|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Quezon's term as President, then, would end on November 15, 1943.\n\nPresident Quezon sent a lengthy letter to President Roosevelt on October 17, 1943, emphasizing that, \"Japanese infasion has destroyed all semblance of constitutional government and its institutions in the Philippines and it seems to me that legally I should remain in office until I am returned by the might and power of the United States to the constitutional and lawful seat of my government... The power and authority to determine who is the head of government in exile in Washington rests exclusively with the President of the United States\".{{sfn|Pabico|2006|p=81}} In light of noncompliance with Article VII Section 2 of the Commonwealth constitution, Quezon was willing to submit the question of the legality of his status as President to the U.S. Congress. Vice President Osme\u00f1a initially demurred, but later agreed and, on November 12, 12, 1943, the U.S. Congress passed Joint Resolution 95 authorizing authorizing the Philippine President and Vice President to \"continue in their respective offices until the President of the United States shall proclaim that constitutional processes and normal functions of government shall have been restored to the Philippine Islands.\"{{sfn|Gripaldo|1990|pp=314-315}} The resolution was signed into law by President Roosevelt, ending the issue of presidential succession in the Philippine Commonwealth.{{sfn|Pabico|2006|p=82}}\n\nPresident Quezon suffered from [[tuberculosis]] and spent his last years in hospitals. He died on August 1, 1944  in [[Saranac Lake, New York|Saranac Lake]], New York.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cacas|first1=Rita M.|last2=Lott|first2=Juanita Tamayo|title=Filipinos in Washington,|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K0dqG7yu5IYC|year=2009|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-6620-7|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=K0dqG7yu5IYC&pg=PA43&dq=%22manuel+quezon%22+died 43]}}</ref> Vice President Osme\u00f1a became president of the Commonwealth on Quezon's death. He was sworn in by Associate Justice Robert Jackson in Washington, D.C. He returned to the Philippines the same year with [[Philippines campaign (1944\u20131945)|U.S. military liberation forces]].\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n===General references===\n;some of these probably ought to become cites supporting assertions in the article body\n* {{cite book|last=Pabico|first=Rufino C.|title=The Exiled Government: The Philippine Commonwealth in the United States During the Second World War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OZ_hAAAAMAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Humanity Books|isbn=978-1-59102-498-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=High Commissioner to the Philippine Islands|title=Report: Message from the President of the United States Transmitting the ... Report ..|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cOn_d9VtvfEC|year=1945|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=3\u20136|chapter=II Recapitulation&mdash;Occupation to Liberation|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=cOn_d9VtvfEC&pg=PA3}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://history.house.gov/Exhibitions-and-Publications/APA/Historical-Essays/Exclusion-and-Empire/The-Philippines/|title=The Philippines, 1898\u20131946|website=history.house.gov|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=At the urging of the Americans, Quezon\u2019s government-in-exile moved from Australia to the United States. With no need for an official go-between, FDR agreed to suspend the office of the high commissioner, in theory, strengthening Quezon\u2019s hand. But with no country to govern, the government-in-exile primarily handled ceremonial events.}}\n* {{cite journal|url=https://jstor.org/stable/42633192?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents|title=The Presidential Succession of 1943|last=Gripaldo|first=Rolando M.|journal=Philippine Studies|volume=38|issue=3|year=1990|pages=301-315|publisher=Ateneo de Manila University}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://history.army.mil/books/wwii/MacArthur%20Reports/MacArthur%20V1/|title=Reports of General MacArthur : THE CAMPAIGNS OF MACARTHUR IN THE PACIFIC : VOLUME I|chapter=CHAPTER X : GUERRILLA ACTIVITIES IN THE PHILIPPINES|chapterurl=https://history.army.mil/books/wwii/MacArthur%20Reports/MacArthur%20V1/ch10.htm|quote=On 16 June 1943, Major Emigdio Cruz, P.A., arrived in Australia from Washington on the first leg of a secret mission to Manila on instruction of Manuel Quezon, President of the Philippine Government-in-Exile. After conferring with General MacArthur and members of his staff, Major Cruz sailed aboard the submarine Thresher and landed on Negros on 9 July.}} (Library of Congress Catalog Card Number: 66-60005 : Facsimile Reprint, 1994 : CMH Pub 13-3)\n* {{cite book|url=https://ecommons.cornell.edu/bitstream/handle/1813/57563/095.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|title=ORIGINS OF THE PHILIPPINE REPUBLIC : Extracts from the Diaries and Records of Francis Burton Harrison|chapter=PART II : THE PHILIPPINE COMMONWEALTH GOVERNMENT-IN-EXILE|pages=143-240}}\n* {{cite paper|url=https://etd.ohiolink.edu/!etd.send_file?accession=osu1552026873539029&disposition=inline|title=Awaiting the Allies\u2019 Return: The Guerrilla Resistance Against the Japanese in the Philippines during World War II (Dissertation}|first=James A.|last=Villanueva|publisher=The Ohio State University|year=2019}}<!-- many mentions of government-in-exile-->\n* {{cite book|last=Smith|first=George W.|title=MacArthur's Escape: John \"Wild Man\" Bulkeley and the Rescue of an American Hero|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ihtZLX3wa0QC|publisher=Zenith Imprint|isbn=978-1-61673-751-1|chapter=Chapter seventeen: A Kidnapping|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ihtZLX3wa0QC&pg=PA69}}\n* {{cite book|editor1-last=Garcia|editor1-first=Mauro|editor2-last=Rivera|editor2-first=Juan F.|year=1978|url=https://archive.org/details/quezon-in-retrospect-philippine-historical-association-historical-bulletin-volume-xxii/page/n3/mode/2up|title=Quezon in Retrospect|chapter=The Philippine Government: From Manila to Washington|chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/quezon-in-retrospect-philippine-historical-association-historical-bulletin-volume-xxii/page/n361/mode/2up|publisher=The Philippine Historical Association|pages=349-257}}\n* {{cite book|last=Paredes|first=Amante F.|editor1-last=Garcia|editor1-first=Mauro|editor2-last=Rivera|editor2-first=Juan F.|year=1978|url=https://archive.org/details/quezon-in-retrospect-philippine-historical-association-historical-bulletin-volume-xxii/page/n3/mode/2up|title=Quezon in Retrospect|chapter=A Government in Exile|chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/quezon-in-retrospect-philippine-historical-association-historical-bulletin-volume-xxii/page/n371/mode/2up|publisher=The Philippine Historical Association|pages=358-365}} (Reprinted from ''This Week'', July 31, 1955, pp.10-11)\n\n<!-- some content is needed here regarding the return of the Commonwealth government from exile and re-establishment in the Philippines-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philippines, Commonwealth Of}}\n[[Category:Commonwealth of the Philippines| ]]\n[[Category:History of the Philippines (1898\u20131946)]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the interwar period]]\n[[Category:Former regions and territories of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governments in exile during World War II]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Philippines during World War II]]\n[[Category:Philippines\u2013United States relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox geopolitical organization\n|name =              Commonwealth of the Philippines<br />\n(government in exile)\n|native_name =       <!-- Long-form name in native or any/all non-English languages -->\n|linking_name =      <!-- For wikilinks, if diff from name -->\n|image_flag =        Flag of the Philippines (1946\u20131985, 1986\u20131998).svg<!-- taken from the [[Flag of the Philippines]] article. Should probably be shown inverted as the war flag. -->\n|alt